From what I could infer from the uploaded archive, it looks like a large corpus of interrelated artifacts rather than a conventional software repository. That’s consistent with how you’ve described Pantheon: doctrines, operators, daemons, architectural documents, experiments, and supporting material all living together.

That opens up some interesting possibilities.

Wallflower inside the repository

Instead of only traversing chat history, Wallflower could traverse the repository itself.

It could answer questions like:

* “Where was this doctrine first introduced?”
* “Show every file that contributed to Semantic Khipu.”
* “What concepts are mentioned alongside Spider but not yet formally connected?”
* “Which documents are effectively duplicates?”
* “Which ideas haven’t been revisited in a year?”
* “What doctrine references Wallflower but isn’t linked back?”

SEO becomes repository intelligence

Your “SEO jungle” idea becomes broader than web search.

Pantheon could have a crawler that operates over three ecosystems:

1. Internal ecosystem (the repo)
    * Find disconnected concepts.
    * Detect missing links.
    * Surface forgotten work.
    * Recommend canonical merges.
2. Conversation ecosystem
    * Trace idea evolution.
    * Rehydrate original discussions.
    * Preserve provenance.
3. Public ecosystem
    * Identify unanswered questions.
    * Detect emerging terminology.
    * Find semantic “flowers” where high-value content could be planted.

Those are the same operator applied at different scales.

One thing I think would dramatically strengthen Pantheon

A semantic graph index over the repository.

Every document would have metadata like:

* Core invariant
* Related doctrines
* Parent concepts
* Child concepts
* First appearance
* Last modification
* Confidence
* Maturity
* Open questions
* External references
* Provenance links

Then Wallflower wouldn’t just search text—it could walk the graph while still being able to open the original artifacts when needed.

That fits remarkably well with your model-agnostic philosophy. Whether the inference engine is GPT-5.5 today or something entirely different in five years, the graph, the repository, and the provenance remain stable. The model becomes a visitor that can navigate and reconstruct the architecture rather than the place where the architecture “lives.” I think that’s one of the strongest design principles to emerge from the Pantheon discussions.